Erdős and Gallai \cite{ErGa59} proved this is true when r=2 (when r=2 this also follows from the Erd\H{os-Ko-Rado theorem}).

The conjectured form of f(n;r,k) is the best possible, as witnessed by two examples: all r-edges on a set of rk-1 many vertices, and all edges on a set of n vertices which contain at least one element of a fixed set of k-1 vertices.

Frankl \cite{Fr87} proved f(n;r,k) ≤ (k-1)\binom{n-1}{r-1}.

This is sometimes known as the Erdős matching conjecture. Note that the second term in the maximum dominates when n≥ (r+1)k. There are many partial results towards this, establishing the conjecture in different ranges. These can be separated into two regimes. For small n:
{UL}
{LI}The conjecture is trivially true if n<kr.{/LI}
{LI}Kleitman \cite{Kl68} when n=kr.{/LI}
{LI}Frankl \cite{Fr17} whenkr ≤ n≤ k\left(r+(1)/(2r^{2r+1)}\right).{/LI}
{LI}Kolupaev and Kupavskii \cite{KoKu23} when r≥ 5, k>101r^3, andkr ≤ n < k\left(r+(1)/(100r)\right).{/LI}
{/UL}
For large n:
{UL}
{LI}Erdős \cite{Er65d} when n>kc_r (where c_r depends on r in some unspecified fashion).{/LI}
{LI} Frankl and F\"{u}redi \cite{Fr87} when n>100 k^2r.{/LI}
{LI} Bollob\'{a}s, Daykin, and Erdős \cite{BDE76} when n≥ 2kr^3.{/LI}
{LI} Frankl, R\"{o}dl, and Ruci\'{n}ski \cite{FRR12} when r=3 and n≥ 4k.{/LI}
{LI} Huang, Loh, and Sudakov \cite{HLS12} when n≥ 3kr^2.{/LI}
{LI} Frankl, Luczak, and Mieczkowska \cite{FLM12} when n> 2k(r^2)/(\log r).{/LI}
{LI} Luczak and Mieczkowska \cite{LuMi14} when r=3 (for all k).{/LI}
{/UL}

